    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "ok that makes sense but it feels weird to just let some company hold onto a chunk of my cash. what if the inspection comes back and shows the foundation is cracked or something? do i just lose that money or how does the escrow thing actually work when stuff goes wrong?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The escrow account is your safety net, even if it feels like you're handing over some of your cash to a third party. If the inspection reveals a major issue, the escrow process kicks in, and it's designed to handle those scenarios. If the inspection uncovers a serious problem, the terms of your contract—and the escrow agreement—will dictate what happens next.\n\nIt's crucial to understand that the earnest money isn't just a fee; it's a form of good faith. If you back out for a reason covered in the contract, you can usually get that money back, or it might be used to cover certain costs, depending on what you agreed upon. You need to review your purchase agreement very carefully to see the specific clauses about inspections and contingencies.",
